  original:"Linux mainly has 2 modes: Graphical Mode (GUI), Command Line Mode (CLI)",
  beginner:"<p>This ties directly back to Q1 and Q19 — Linux can run in two modes. <b>Graphical Mode (GUI)</b> looks and feels like Windows or macOS, with icons, windows, and a mouse-driven desktop. <b>Command Line Mode (CLI)</b> shows only a text prompt where you type commands — no icons, no mouse required. Both modes run the exact same underlying Linux system; the difference is purely whether a graphical desktop environment is installed and running on top.</p>",
  why:"<p>Servers don't need a screen or a mouse sitting in front of them in a data center — running CLI-only saves system resources (RAM, CPU, disk space) that would otherwise be spent running a graphical desktop nobody is looking at, exactly why \"Minimal\" install (Q19) skips the GUI entirely.</p>",
  real:"<p>A company's developers use Ubuntu Desktop (GUI mode) on their laptops for a familiar, visual coding environment, while the exact same code gets deployed to production Linux servers running in CLI-only mode, since those servers are managed entirely over SSH with no one ever needing to see a desktop.</p>",
  interview:"Linux mainly runs in two modes: Graphical Mode (GUI), with a full desktop environment for visual interaction, and Command Line Mode (CLI), a text-only interface. Servers typically run CLI-only to save resources, while desktop/laptop use typically runs GUI mode.",
